 automake,
 libtool,
# --- Hardware / network / shell utilities (heritage from AIMS Desktop)
# bc — CLI calculator, expected by Bash users and many shell scripts.
# lshw — list hardware (model, drivers) for support / troubleshooting.
# smartmontools — disk health (SMART). Critical for AIMS lab machines
#     where students keep their thesis data on aging drives.
# zram-tools — compressed swap on RAM. Big win on older lab laptops
#     with 4 GB RAM. AIMS Desktop 2020 shipped this for the same
#     reason; default zramswap.service kicks in at boot.
# wireless-tools — legacy iwconfig / iwlist. Lots of networking
#     tutorials still reference these even though NetworkManager
#     manages everything; keep them so `iwconfig wlan0` works.
# rfkill — toggle wireless / Bluetooth via CLI (`rfkill block wifi`).
# command-not-found — when a user types `htopx`, suggests `htop`.
# wamerican / wfrench — system word lists used by ispell/aspell,
#     spell-check in editors, password generators. AIMS Desktop
#     shipped these via `task-french` already (we pull it).
 bc,
 lshw,
 smartmontools,
 zram-tools,
 wireless-tools,
 rfkill,
 command-not-found,
Description: AIMS OS — system-level baseline
 This metapackage installs the AIMS OS core system: the host firewall
 (UFW), AppArmor mandatory access control, automatic Debian-Security
 upgrades and fail2ban; the firmware blobs required for typical Wi-Fi
 chipsets and discrete GPUs seen in Senegalese lab hardware; the
 French locale and desktop support task packages so the system speaks
 French out of the box; ACPI and time-synchronisation daemons; common
 filesystem and block-layer tools (ext, exFAT, NTFS, LVM, LUKS); the
 CLI utilities expected on a modern developer workstation; and the
 GCC / gfortran / make / cmake build toolchain that AIMS C and Fortran
 coursework depends on.
 .
 Installing this metapackage on a vanilla Debian Trixie replicates
 the system-level baseline an AIMS OS install ships with, without
 touching the desktop or scientific stack.
